      <!-- Content -->
      <main class="docs-content">
        <h1>Getting Started</h1>
        <p>Get gflow installed and running in under 2 minutes.</p>

        <h2 id="install">Installation</h2>

        <h3>Go Install (recommended)</h3>
        <p>If you have Go 1.22+ installed:</p>
        <pre><code>go install github.com/abhinavcdev/gflow@latest</code></pre>

        <h3>From Source</h3>
        <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/abhinavcdev/gflow.git
cd gflow
make build
sudo mv bin/gflow /usr/local/bin/</code></pre>

        <h3>Verify</h3>
        <pre><code>gflow version</code></pre>

        <h2 id="token">GitHub Token Setup</h2>
        <p>gflow needs a GitHub Personal Access Token to create PRs, manage releases, and configure branch protection.</p>

        <h3>Generate a token</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <a href="https://github.com/settings/tokens" target="_blank">github.com/settings/tokens</a></li>
          <li>Click <strong>"Generate new token"</strong> &rarr; <strong>"Generate new token (classic)"</strong></li>
          <li>Name it <code>gflow</code></li>
          <li>Select the <strong><code>repo</code></strong> scope (full control of private repositories)</li>
          <li>Click <strong>"Generate token"</strong> and copy it</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Set it in your shell</h3>
        <pre><code>export GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx</code></pre>

        <h3>Make it permanent</h3>
        <pre><code># zsh (default on macOS)
echo 'export GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_xxxx' >> ~/.zshrc
source ~/.zshrc

# bash
echo 'export GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_xxxx' >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc</code></pre>

        <p><strong>Security note:</strong> gflow reads the token from the <code>GITHUB_TOKEN</code> environment variable. It is <em>never</em> stored in <code>.gflow.yml</code> or committed to git.</p>

        <h2 id="init">Initialize gflow</h2>
        <p>Navigate to your repository and run the setup wizard:</p>
        <pre><code>cd your-repo
gflow init</code></pre>

        <p>The wizard will:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Auto-detect your GitHub repository from the git remote</li>
          <li>Check for your GitHub token</li>
          <li>Ask about branching conventions (prefixes, main branch)</li>
          <li>Set PR defaults (merge method, draft mode, reviewers)</li>
          <li>Configure commit conventions</li>
          <li>Write a <code>.gflow.yml</code> file</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Tip:</strong> Commit <code>.gflow.yml</code> to your repo so your entire team shares the same conventions.</p>

        <h2 id="first-workflow">Your First Workflow</h2>

        <h3>1. Start a feature branch</h3>
        <pre><code>gflow start feature user-auth</code></pre>
        <p>Creates <code>feature/user-auth</code> from <code>main</code>, synced with remote.</p>

        <h3>2. Make your changes</h3>
        <p>Write code as usual. Use <code>gflow commit</code> for interactive conventional commits, or commit normally.</p>
        <pre><code>gflow commit</code></pre>

        <h3>3. Open a PR</h3>
        <pre><code>gflow pr "Add user authentication"</code></pre>
        <p>This single command stages all changes, commits, pushes, and opens a pull request with your configured labels and settings.</p>

        <h3>4. Check the dashboard</h3>
        <pre><code>gflow dash</code></pre>
        <p>See your branch, PR status, CI checks, and recent commits — all fetched in parallel.</p>

        <h3>5. Merge and clean up</h3>
        <pre><code>gflow finish</code></pre>
        <p>Checks CI status, merges the PR, deletes the branch, and switches back to main.</p>

        <div style="margin-top: var(--space-3xl); padding: var(--space-xl); background: var(--bg-card); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--radius-lg);">
